summary:
❝No more tears❞
  Sansa wakes up with a start looking for Theon. She is alone in the darkness that surrounds her, almost as...
body:
❝No more tears❞

 Sansa wakes up with a start looking for Theon. She is alone in the darkness that surrounds her, almost as if it’s already dragging her into an abyss. She screams out loud.

 He rushes to the door of her room, but he hesitates for an instant since fear seizes him. He pulls down the handle, he crosses the threshold and he approaches her. He lets her cling desperately to him.

Theon imagines Sansa reborn among the waves of the brackish sea: what is dead may never die, but rises again harder and stronger.

——  Sansa x Theon aesthetic |  © caption by me.

summary: I'm trying to figure out where people got this idea that women actually have a choice in who they will marry in the asoiaf...
question: I'm trying to figure out where people got this idea that women actually have a choice in who they will marry in the asoiaf series. Women didn't have choices like that. They were specifically "bred" to be a wife. I think of how people act like Sansa had a choice in marrying Joffrey. Even if she didn't want him, she was going to marry him. Arya was going to marry a Frey at one point, in exchange for a bridge passage. Her hand was offered in a deal without her consent. That should tell us enough.
answer:
They don’t! Sansa didn’t decide it, her parents did as a cover for Ned’s investigation. She didn’t even start claiming to be in love with Joffrey (by comparing the two of them to historical romances and fairytales while showing far more excitement for the tourney than him) until Lady was killed and that ‘love’ was tempered with fear. Sansa going to Cersei was about staying in King’s Landing more than Joffrey.

They do the same thing to Catelyn and Elia, accusing them of choosing their husbands but they didn’t. Their parents arranged it. Reneging on an arranged marriage has huge social and political consequences.
